THE case against 17 suspects accused of killings that happened in Marikana in 2012 appeared in the North West Division of the High Court on Wednesday, 8 March. They have been charged with seven counts of murder, malicious damage to property, and robbery. North West National Prosecuting Authority (NPA) spokesman Henry Mamothame said the charges are related to the labour disputes between mine workers and their employers during an unprotected wage strike. "The matter was set for trial from 6 to 10 March. However, one of the accused was not present on the first day and the matter was rolled over to the next day,” Mamothame said. ALSO READ | Party not coping and wants answers! The state indicated that it was ready to proceed with the trial, however, the defence attorneys wanted the matter to be postponed or struck off the roll, pending the outcome of the review application to have all charges withdrawn. "Both the state and the accused’s legal representatives have completed their arguments and the sitting judge is expected to make a judgment on Friday, 10 March on the postponement,” Mamothame added. You must be SIGNED IN to read comments The state emphasised that its witnesses are ready to testify in the matter," he said. 